Package jetbrains.mps.workbench.choose

Class ChooseByNameData<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • jetbrains.mps.workbench.choose.ChooseByNameData<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - elements of the list to choose from. No restriction (e.g. like need for Object.hashCode() is imposed on elements.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.intellij.ide.util.gotoByName.ChooseByNameModel
    public final class ChooseByNameData<T>
extends Object
implements com.intellij.ide.util.gotoByName.ChooseByNameModel
    Data model for a chooser that picks elements by name. Supports two 'scopes' of elements to pick from, 'local' and 'global' that may correspond e.g. to project and application or locally-visible vs visible in the project elements.

    Replacement for jetbrains.mps.workbench.choose.base.BaseMPSChooseModel, with composition rather than inheritance as usage pattern, and without need to know about peculiarities of NavigationItem, ItemPresentation and correspondence of their methods to methods of ChooseByNameModel, like NavigationItem.getName() vs ChooseByNameModel.getElementName(Object) vs ItemPresentation.getPresentableText(). Besides, dumb mode control has nothing to do with choose model, and left to callers for management.

    Generally, there's no need to sub-class this class, composition should be enough, hence final. Nevertheless, the class is not inherently 'final', and in case there's legitimate scenario that requires subclassing, 'final' can be removed. 'Legitimate', among other, means documented justification with specific scenarios. XXX perhaps, it's worth adding own callback, parameterized, to avoid casts to in Callback.elementChosen(). Alternative is to ressurect getModelObject like in BaseMPSChooseModel (where it was needed because user objects were wrapped with NavigationItem) which would cast to . I don't like unchecked casts, though, that's why I don't fall into this alternative right away.

    Since:
    3.4

      • derivePrompts

        public ChooseByNameData<T> derivePrompts​(String elementName)
        Tribute to BaseMPSChooseModel constructor that composed prompts based on generic name of an element. Note, in addition to values initialized with setPrompts(String, String, String), derives value for getCheckBoxName() as well. If you don't need checkbox, don't forget to setCheckBoxName(String) to null.
        Returns:
        this for convenience

      • setScope

        public final ChooseByNameData<T> setScope​(@NotNull
                                          Iterable<T> localScope,
                                          @Nullable
                                          Iterable<T> globalScope)
        Configure chooser. Invoke this method prior to use of the model. Perhaps, need an alternative constructor that would take scope as well.

        The choice of Iterable for scope is not a sure thing. I don't see a point for a custom interface here; Supplier<Iterable<T>> looks bit too much, and Iterable seems quite handy with streams.

        Parameters:
        localScope - default set of elements, available without extras/global staff made available with checkbox
        globalScope - extended set of elements, available on explicit request from user. null indicates same scope as local shall be used. This is done to facilitate in-place local scope creation (new) without a need to extract a local variable. Though unlikely needed, explicit empty scope shall get passed if it's true to get nothing at global scope (any empty collection would do).
        Returns:
        this for convenience
